<section class="stor" aria-labelledby="stor-headline">
  <p class="label">The shift</p>
  <h2 id="stor-headline">From snowflake chaos to a standard runtime.</h2>

  <div class="stor-vignette point-a">
    <p>Your first Cursor-built <strong>ticketing tool</strong> took a weekend.</p>
    <p>
      The fourth — a <strong>customer-ops console</strong> — has a migration your team lead refuses to run.
      The <strong>back-office dashboard</strong> you built last month passes tests, but fires two events on every retry.
      You spent more time reviewing AI diffs last month than writing anything new.
    </p>
    <p><em>The agent didn't slow down. Your architecture did.</em></p>
  </div>

  <div class="stor-vignette point-b">
    <p class="stor-shift">Shift →</p>
    <p>A week from now, service #5 is a blueprint you edited in 40 minutes.</p>
    <p>
      The runtime is the same one #1 runs. The diff is 12 lines of JSON.
      Your team lead signs off in five minutes — the runtime didn't change, only the domain.
      You tell the agent "build an escalation flow" and it writes a blueprint, not a repo.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

